  "text": "Implications to evolutionary medicine As mentioned above, the variation in the GSTM locus has been the subject of more than 500 studies within the context of multiple diseases [CITATION_1] . However, given that majority of these studies are correlations, they lack mechanistic or evolutionary insights as to why the genetic variation in this locus is relevant. The emerging picture is that of a gene family (GSTM1-5) that broadly metabolizes multiple carcinogenic substances, for example, 4-nitroquinoline-1-oxide (NQO) [CITATION_2] . On top of that functional layer, it has been shown that this gene family is riddled with common genetic variation, including the unusually common deletion of the GSTM1. These genetic variants, as expected, were associated with multiple cancers [CITATION_3] . The mechanistic explanation would be that the reduced the GSTM function leads to higher susceptibility to carcinogenic substance exposure [CITATION_4] .",
